{"title_page": "Buckhaven and Methil", "text_new": "{{unreferenced|date=June 2012}}'''Buckhaven and Methil''' was a [[Burgh]] of Scotland, centred on the towns of [[Buckhaven]] and [[Methil]]. It formed in 1891 and was abolished in 1975.\n\nBuckhaven and Methil exist today as two towns although both are within the [[Levenmouth]] area according to a description given by [[Fife Council]].\n\nIn 1983 There was a big thing involving aching\n\n==See also==\n*[[Levenmouth]]\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Burghs]]\n\n\n{{Scotland-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{unreferenced|date=June 2012}}'''Buckhaven and Methil''' was a [[Burgh]] of Scotland, centred on the towns of [[Buckhaven]] and [[Methil]]. It formed in 1891 and was abolished in 1975.\n\nBuckhaven and Methil exist today as two towns although both are within the [[Levenmouth]] area according to a description given by [[Fife Council]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Levenmouth]]\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Burghs]]\n\n\n{{Scotland-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Phonetic007", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buckhaven_and_Methil"}
{"title_page": "Scott D. Tingle", "text_new": "{{Infobox astronaut\n| name          = Scott D. Tingle\n| image         = Scott D. Tingle, official portrait.jpg\n| type          = [[NASA]] Astronaut\n| status        = Active\n| nationality   = American\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1965|7|19}}\n| birth_place   = [[Attleboro, Massachusetts]], U.S.\n| rank          = [[Captain (United States)|Captain]], [[United States Navy|USN]]\n| occupation    = Test pilot\n| selection     = [[NASA Astronaut Group 20|2009 NASA Group]]\n| space_time    = 168 days 5 hours 18 minutes\n| eva1     = 1\n| eva2    = 7 hours 24 minutes\n| missions      = [[Soyuz MS-07]] ([[Expedition 54]]/[[Expedition 55|55]])\n| insignia      = [[Image:Soyuz-MS-07-Mission-Patch.png|50px]] [[Image:ISS Expedition 54 Patch.svg|55px]] [[Image:ISS Expedition 55 Patch.svg|50px]]| awards        = [[File:Meritorious Service w medal.svg|20px|link=Meritorious Service Medal (United States)]] [[File:Air Medal front.jpg|20px|link=Air Medal]] [[File:Air Force Commendation Medal.jpg|20px|link=Commendation Medal]] [[File:\"V\" device, brass.png|20px|link=\"V\" device]]\n}}\n\n'''Scott David Tingle''' (born July 19, 1965) is a [[NASA]] [[astronaut]].<ref name=\"newclass\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nasa.gov/astronauts/ascans2009.html |title=NASA Selects New Astronauts for Future Space Exploration |last=NASA HQ |date=June 29, 2009 |publisher=[[NASA]] |accessdate=June 29, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090801162824/http://www.nasa.gov/astronauts/ascans2009.html |archivedate=August 1, 2009}}</ref> He was selected in June 2009 as a member of the [[NASA Astronaut Group 20]], qualifying in 2011. Serving as a flight engineer as part of [[Expedition 54]] and [[Expedition 55|55]], Tingle launched into space on board [[Soyuz MS-07]] in December 2017, and returned in June 2018.<ref name=\"launch\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2017/12/soyuz-ms-07-final-human-launch-2017/ |title=Soyuz MS-07 launches on final human mission of 2017|date=December 17, 2017|author=Chris Gebhardt| publisher=nasaspaceflight.com}}</ref> Tingle is a highly decorated naval pilot, having flown 51 types of aircraft over more than 4,500 flight hours, landed 750 aircraft with [[Arresting gear|carrier arrestments]], and fought in 54 combat missions.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nasa.gov/astronauts/biographies/scott-d-tingle/biography|title=Scott D. Tingle (Captain, U.S. Navy) NASA Astronaut|last=Whiting|first=Melanie|date=2016-02-16|work=NASA|access-date=2018-03-08|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early years and education==\nScott Tingle is a Commander in the [[U.S. Navy]]. He was born Scott D. Tingle in [[Attleboro, Massachusetts]]. Tingle became interested in space while working as a machine draftsman in [[Blue Hills Regional Technical School]], class of 1983.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2018/01/08/started-zeppy-bakery-randolph-now-about-miles-above-earth/o0vJPsdIcBYQlUGn5Zm5SM/story.html|title=He started at Zeppy's Bakery in Randolph. Now he's about 250 miles above Earth. - The Boston Globe|work=BostonGlobe.com|access-date=2018-02-13}}</ref> He continued to study mechanical engineering, earning a Bachelor of Science in Mechanical Engineering while attending [[University of Massachusetts Dartmouth|Southeastern Massachusetts University]] in 1987, and a Master of Science in Mechanical Engineering from [[Purdue University]] in 1988.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/htmlbios/tingle.html|title=Bio: Scott D. Tingle|last=NASA|date=September 2009|publisher=NASA|accessdate=2009-10-11}}</ref> In 2009 his fourth application to the Astronaut Corps was accepted.\n\n== Military service ==\nIn 1991 Scott Tingle employed as a [[Officer (armed forces)|Naval Officer]], earning his aviator gold wings by 1993. In 1994 he flew with the [[VFA-146|Blue Diamonds]] of VFA-146 in [[Lemoore, California]]. Aboard the [[USS Nimitz]] and with [[Carrier Air Wing Nine]] he was placed along the [[Persian Gulf]] and Western [[Pacific ocean]]. After graduating in 1998 from [[United States Naval Test Pilot School|Navy Test Pilot School]], he became an operational test pilot at [[Naval Air Weapons Station China Lake|China Lake, California]] for the [[Boeing F/A-18E/F Super Hornet|FA-18E/F]] Super Hornet program with the Vampires of [[VX-9]]. After China Lake, Tingle completed a [[Landing signal officer|CAG Paddles]] tour flying with FA-18A/C Hornets and alongside [[Carrier Air Wing Eleven]] (CVW-11) sailing on the [[USS Carl Vinson]]. USS Carl Vinson and the Carrier Air Wing Eleven were the first air response on the scene of the 911 attack and later executed [[Operation Enduring Freedom]] in Afghanistan. Tingle completed a career as an assistant operations officer with the Strike Fighter Wing Pacific, and briefly became an instructor pilot with [[VFA-102|VFA-122]]. He later returned to Lemoore as a safety, maintenance, and operation officer as a department head while flying a FA-18A Hornet alongside the [[VFA-97|Warhawks of VFA-97]]. He was deployed to the Western Pacific and Persian Gulf again with CVW-11 before moving on to [[Iwakuni, Japan]], with the Marine Air Group Twelve (MAH-12). By 2005 Tingle came back to become the Ship Suitability Department Head at [[Patuxent River|Patuxent River, Maryland]], and a test pilot with the [[VX-23|Salty Dogs of VX-23]]. At Maryland he tested the [[McDonnell Douglas F/A-18 Hornet|FA-18C Hornet]], [[Boeing F/A-18E/F Super Hornet|FA-18E/F Super Hornet]], and [[Boeing EA-18G Growler|EA-18G Growler]] aircraft carrier precision landing systems. When he was selected as an astronaut Tingle was working on the [[AGM-84E Standoff Land Attack Missile|Standoff Land Attack Missile]] (SLAM) and harpoon weapons systems in [[Precision-guided munition|PMA-201]] as a system engineer and assistant program manager.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==NASA career==\nIn July 2009 Scott D Tingle became a member of the 20th astronaut class. His training included training in T-38's, spacewalks, technical training regarding the systems of The International space station and [[Soyuz (spacecraft)|Soyuz]] designs, and standard wilderness survival training. In December 2017 he launched on [[Soyuz MS-07]] as the flight engineer, and will remain on the [[International Space Station|international space station]] until April 2018. His mission on [[Expedition 54|Expedition 54/55]] has a focus on experiments involving biology, biotechnology, and demonstrations of new technology on the ISS.<ref name=\":22\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/station/expeditions/expedition54/index.html|title=Expedition 54|last=Dunbar|first=Brian|date=2017-11-29|work=NASA|access-date=2018-03-15|archive-url=|archive-date=|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Expedition 54/55===\nIt was announced that Tingle would launch to the ISS for his first spaceflight in December 2017, as a flight engineer for [[Expedition 54]] and [[Expedition 55]]. Tingle launched on board [[Soyuz MS-07]] on December 17, 2017 07:21 UTC.<ref name=\"launch\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2017/12/soyuz-ms-07-final-human-launch-2017/ |title=Soyuz MS-07 launches on final human mission of 2017|date=December 17, 2017|author=Chris Gebhardt| publisher=nasaspaceflight.com}}</ref>\n[[File:ISS-54 EVA-1 (a) Scott Tingle.jpg|thumb|left| Tingle pictured during his first EVA]]\nOn January 23, 2018, Tingle performed his first EVA with [[Mark Vande Hei]]. The objective was to replace one of two redundant latching end effectors (LEE) on [[Canadarm2]], the station's robotic arm, which had experienced some degradation of its snaring cables. The duration of the EVA was 7 hours and 24 minutes.<ref>{{Citation|last=space googlevesaire|title=LIVE \ud83d\udd34 SPACEWALK ISS 54 Flight Engineer Mark Vande Hei and Flight Engineer Scott Tingle|date=2018-01-23|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=009Lq7nzmVE|accessdate=2018-03-15}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nScott Tingle is married to Raynette Mahelona Tingle and has three children. Although he was born in Attleboro, he considers his hometown to be [[Randolph, Massachusetts]].<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite news|url=https://engineering.purdue.edu/Engr/News/tingle|title=Scott Tingle Becomes Purdue's 23rd Astronaut|work=College of Engineering - Purdue University|access-date=2018-03-08|language=en}}</ref> At age 15 he took guitar lessons from a neighbor, at age 16 he joined a band that he continued to play with through college, writing original music and playing at clubs in [[Kenmore Square]], and [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]]. Tingle cites his experience in a rock band as contributing to team skills he needed as an astronaut.<ref>{{Citation|last=NASA Johnson|title=Astronaut Moments: Scott Tingle: Guitarist|date=2018-01-26|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=02QbU89KzWc|accessdate=2018-03-08}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and honors ==\nThrough his educational, military, and NASA career, Tingle has received many awards and honors. He graduated magna cum laude from Southeastern Massachusetts University, earned Outstanding Graduate of [[United States Naval Test Pilot School|U.S. Navy Test Pilot School]] Class 113, and was awarded [[Meritorious Service Medal (United States)|Meritorious Service]] Medal, three [[Air Medal]]s, six [[Navy Commendation Medal|Navy Commendation]] Medals, four [[Achievement Medal|Navy and Marine Corps Achievement]] Medals, and a [[\"V\" device|Combat V]] medal.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Include-NASA}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/htmlbios/tingle.html Astronaut Bio: Scott D. Tingle (09/2009)]\n* [http://www.spacefacts.de/bios/astronauts/english/tingle_scott.htm Spacefacts biography of Scott D. Tingle]\n* {{twitter}}\n\n{{NASA Astronaut Group 20}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tingle, Scott David}}\n[[Category:American astronauts]]\n[[Category:American test pilots]]\n[[Category:University of Massachusetts Dartmouth alumni]]\n[[Category:Purdue University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:People from Attleboro, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:United States Navy officers]]\n[[Category:People from Randolph, Massachusetts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox astronaut\n| name          = Scott D. Tingle\n| image         = Scott D. Tingle, official portrait.jpg\n| type          = [[NASA]] Astronaut\n| status        = Active\n| nationality   = American\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1965|7|19}}\n| birth_place   = [[Attleboro, Massachusetts]], U.S.\n| rank          = [[Captain (United States)|Captain]], [[United States Navy|USN]]\n| occupation    = Test pilot\n| selection     = [[NASA Astronaut Group 20|2009 NASA Group]]\n| space_time    = 168 days 5 hours 18 minutes\n| eva1     = 1\n| eva2    = 7 hours 24 minutes\n| missions      = [[Soyuz MS-07]] ([[Expedition 54]]/[[Expedition 55|55]])\n| insignia      = [[Image:Soyuz-MS-07-Mission-Patch.png|50px]] [[Image:ISS Expedition 54 Patch.svg|50px]] [[Image:ISS Expedition 55 Patch.svg|50px]]| awards        = [[File:Meritorious Service w medal.svg|20px|link=Meritorious Service Medal (United States)]] [[File:Air Medal front.jpg|20px|link=Air Medal]] [[File:Air Force Commendation Medal.jpg|20px|link=Commendation Medal]] [[File:\"V\" device, brass.png|20px|link=\"V\" device]]\n}}\n\n'''Scott David Tingle''' (born July 19, 1965) is a [[NASA]] [[astronaut]].<ref name=\"newclass\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nasa.gov/astronauts/ascans2009.html |title=NASA Selects New Astronauts for Future Space Exploration |last=NASA HQ |date=June 29, 2009 |publisher=[[NASA]] |accessdate=June 29, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090801162824/http://www.nasa.gov/astronauts/ascans2009.html |archivedate=August 1, 2009}}</ref> He was selected in June 2009 as a member of the [[NASA Astronaut Group 20]], qualifying in 2011. Serving as a flight engineer as part of [[Expedition 54]] and [[Expedition 55|55]], Tingle launched into space on board [[Soyuz MS-07]] in December 2017, and returned in June 2018.<ref name=\"launch\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2017/12/soyuz-ms-07-final-human-launch-2017/ |title=Soyuz MS-07 launches on final human mission of 2017|date=December 17, 2017|author=Chris Gebhardt| publisher=nasaspaceflight.com}}</ref> Tingle is a highly decorated naval pilot, having flown 51 types of aircraft over more than 4,500 flight hours, landed 750 aircraft with [[Arresting gear|carrier arrestments]], and fought in 54 combat missions.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nasa.gov/astronauts/biographies/scott-d-tingle/biography|title=Scott D. Tingle (Captain, U.S. Navy) NASA Astronaut|last=Whiting|first=Melanie|date=2016-02-16|work=NASA|access-date=2018-03-08|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early years and education==\nScott Tingle is a Commander in the [[U.S. Navy]]. He was born Scott D. Tingle in [[Attleboro, Massachusetts]]. Tingle became interested in space while working as a machine draftsman in [[Blue Hills Regional Technical School]], class of 1983.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2018/01/08/started-zeppy-bakery-randolph-now-about-miles-above-earth/o0vJPsdIcBYQlUGn5Zm5SM/story.html|title=He started at Zeppy's Bakery in Randolph. Now he's about 250 miles above Earth. - The Boston Globe|work=BostonGlobe.com|access-date=2018-02-13}}</ref> He continued to study mechanical engineering, earning a Bachelor of Science in Mechanical Engineering while attending [[University of Massachusetts Dartmouth|Southeastern Massachusetts University]] in 1987, and a Master of Science in Mechanical Engineering from [[Purdue University]] in 1988.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/htmlbios/tingle.html|title=Bio: Scott D. Tingle|last=NASA|date=September 2009|publisher=NASA|accessdate=2009-10-11}}</ref> In 2009 his fourth application to the Astronaut Corps was accepted.\n\n== Military service ==\nIn 1991 Scott Tingle employed as a [[Officer (armed forces)|Naval Officer]], earning his aviator gold wings by 1993. In 1994 he flew with the [[VFA-146|Blue Diamonds]] of VFA-146 in [[Lemoore, California]]. Aboard the [[USS Nimitz]] and with [[Carrier Air Wing Nine]] he was placed along the [[Persian Gulf]] and Western [[Pacific ocean]]. After graduating in 1998 from [[United States Naval Test Pilot School|Navy Test Pilot School]], he became an operational test pilot at [[Naval Air Weapons Station China Lake|China Lake, California]] for the [[Boeing F/A-18E/F Super Hornet|FA-18E/F]] Super Hornet program with the Vampires of [[VX-9]]. After China Lake, Tingle completed a [[Landing signal officer|CAG Paddles]] tour flying with FA-18A/C Hornets and alongside [[Carrier Air Wing Eleven]] (CVW-11) sailing on the [[USS Carl Vinson]]. USS Carl Vinson and the Carrier Air Wing Eleven were the first air response on the scene of the 911 attack and later executed [[Operation Enduring Freedom]] in Afghanistan. Tingle completed a career as an assistant operations officer with the Strike Fighter Wing Pacific, and briefly became an instructor pilot with [[VFA-102|VFA-122]]. He later returned to Lemoore as a safety, maintenance, and operation officer as a department head while flying a FA-18A Hornet alongside the [[VFA-97|Warhawks of VFA-97]]. He was deployed to the Western Pacific and Persian Gulf again with CVW-11 before moving on to [[Iwakuni, Japan]], with the Marine Air Group Twelve (MAH-12). By 2005 Tingle came back to become the Ship Suitability Department Head at [[Patuxent River|Patuxent River, Maryland]], and a test pilot with the [[VX-23|Salty Dogs of VX-23]]. At Maryland he tested the [[McDonnell Douglas F/A-18 Hornet|FA-18C Hornet]], [[Boeing F/A-18E/F Super Hornet|FA-18E/F Super Hornet]], and [[Boeing EA-18G Growler|EA-18G Growler]] aircraft carrier precision landing systems. When he was selected as an astronaut Tingle was working on the [[AGM-84E Standoff Land Attack Missile|Standoff Land Attack Missile]] (SLAM) and harpoon weapons systems in [[Precision-guided munition|PMA-201]] as a system engineer and assistant program manager.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==NASA career==\nIn July 2009 Scott D Tingle became a member of the 20th astronaut class. His training included training in T-38's, spacewalks, technical training regarding the systems of The International space station and [[Soyuz (spacecraft)|Soyuz]] designs, and standard wilderness survival training. In December 2017 he launched on [[Soyuz MS-07]] as the flight engineer, and will remain on the [[International Space Station|international space station]] until April 2018. His mission on [[Expedition 54|Expedition 54/55]] has a focus on experiments involving biology, biotechnology, and demonstrations of new technology on the ISS.<ref name=\":22\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/station/expeditions/expedition54/index.html|title=Expedition 54|last=Dunbar|first=Brian|date=2017-11-29|work=NASA|access-date=2018-03-15|archive-url=|archive-date=|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Expedition 54/55===\nIt was announced that Tingle would launch to the ISS for his first spaceflight in December 2017, as a flight engineer for [[Expedition 54]] and [[Expedition 55]]. Tingle launched on board [[Soyuz MS-07]] on December 17, 2017 07:21 UTC.<ref name=\"launch\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2017/12/soyuz-ms-07-final-human-launch-2017/ |title=Soyuz MS-07 launches on final human mission of 2017|date=December 17, 2017|author=Chris Gebhardt| publisher=nasaspaceflight.com}}</ref>\n[[File:ISS-54 EVA-1 (a) Scott Tingle.jpg|thumb|left| Tingle pictured during his first EVA]]\nOn January 23, 2018, Tingle performed his first EVA with [[Mark Vande Hei]]. The objective was to replace one of two redundant latching end effectors (LEE) on [[Canadarm2]], the station's robotic arm, which had experienced some degradation of its snaring cables. The duration of the EVA was 7 hours and 24 minutes.<ref>{{Citation|last=space googlevesaire|title=LIVE \ud83d\udd34 SPACEWALK ISS 54 Flight Engineer Mark Vande Hei and Flight Engineer Scott Tingle|date=2018-01-23|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=009Lq7nzmVE|accessdate=2018-03-15}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nScott Tingle is married to Raynette Mahelona Tingle and has three children. Although he was born in Attleboro, he considers his hometown to be [[Randolph, Massachusetts]].<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite news|url=https://engineering.purdue.edu/Engr/News/tingle|title=Scott Tingle Becomes Purdue's 23rd Astronaut|work=College of Engineering - Purdue University|access-date=2018-03-08|language=en}}</ref> At age 15 he took guitar lessons from a neighbor, at age 16 he joined a band that he continued to play with through college, writing original music and playing at clubs in [[Kenmore Square]], and [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]]. Tingle cites his experience in a rock band as contributing to team skills he needed as an astronaut.<ref>{{Citation|last=NASA Johnson|title=Astronaut Moments: Scott Tingle: Guitarist|date=2018-01-26|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=02QbU89KzWc|accessdate=2018-03-08}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and honors ==\nThrough his educational, military, and NASA career, Tingle has received many awards and honors. He graduated magna cum laude from Southeastern Massachusetts University, earned Outstanding Graduate of [[United States Naval Test Pilot School|U.S. Navy Test Pilot School]] Class 113, and was awarded [[Meritorious Service Medal (United States)|Meritorious Service]] Medal, three [[Air Medal]]s, six [[Navy Commendation Medal|Navy Commendation]] Medals, four [[Achievement Medal|Navy and Marine Corps Achievement]] Medals, and a [[\"V\" device|Combat V]] medal.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Include-NASA}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/htmlbios/tingle.html Astronaut Bio: Scott D. Tingle (09/2009)]\n* [http://www.spacefacts.de/bios/astronauts/english/tingle_scott.htm Spacefacts biography of Scott D. Tingle]\n* {{twitter}}\n\n{{NASA Astronaut Group 20}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tingle, Scott David}}\n[[Category:American astronauts]]\n[[Category:American test pilots]]\n[[Category:University of Massachusetts Dartmouth alumni]]\n[[Category:Purdue University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:People from Attleboro, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:United States Navy officers]]\n[[Category:People from Randolph, Massachusetts]]\n", "name_user": "Toby6250", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scott_D._Tingle"}
{"title_page": "1878 Yale Bulldogs football team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox college sports team season\n| mode = football\n| year = 1878\n| team = Yale Bulldogs\n| image = \n| image_size =  \n| conference = Independent\n| record = 4\u20131\u20131\n| head_coach = None\n| captain = [[Walter Camp]]\n| stadium = [[Hamilton Park (New Haven)|Hamilton Park]]\n\n}}\n{{1878 college football records}}\nThe '''1878 Yale Bulldogs football team''' represented [[Yale University]] in the [[1878 college football season]]. The Bulldogs finished with a 4\u20131\u20131 record. The team recorded five shutouts and outscored its opponents by a combined total of 7 to 1.<ref>{{cite web|title=1878 Yale Bulldogs Schedule and Results|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=SR/College Football|accessdate=February 27, 2017|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/yale/1878-schedule.html}}</ref><ref name=SR>{{cite web|title=2015 Yale Football|url=http://www.yalebulldogs.com/sports/m-footbl/2015-16/files/year_by_year_results_thru_2015.pdf|website=yalebulldogs.com|publisher=Yale Athletics|accessdate=December 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CFB schedule\n\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 2\n| w/l = w\n| opponent = [[1878 Amherst Lord Jeffs football team|Amherst]]\n| site_stadium = [[Hamilton Park (New Haven)|Hamilton Park]]\n| site_cityst = [[New Haven, Connecticut|New Haven, CT]]\n| score = 2\u20130\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 9\n| w/l = w\n| neutral = y\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1878|team=Trinity Bantams|title=Trinity (CT)}}\n| site_stadium = \n| site_cityst = [[Hartford, Connecticut|Hartford, CT]]\n| score = 2\u20130\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 13\n| w/l = w\n| neutral = y\n| opponent = Trinity (CT)\n| site_stadium = \n| site_cityst = Hartford, CT\n| score = 3\u20130\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 16\n| w/l = t\n| opponent = Amherst\n| site_stadium = \n| site_cityst = [[Amherst, Massachusetts|Amherst, MA]]\n| score = 0\u20130\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 23\n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| opponent = [[1878 Harvard Crimson football team|Harvard]]\n| gamename = [[Harvard\u2013Yale football rivalry|rivalry]]\n| site_stadium = [[South End Grounds]]\n| site_cityst = [[Boston|Boston, MA]]\n| score = 1\u20130\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 28\n| w/l = l\n| neutral = y\n| opponent = [[1878 Princeton Tigers football team|Princeton]]\n| site_stadium = \n| site_cityst = [[Hoboken, New Jersey|Hoboken, NJ]]\n| gamename = [[Princeton\u2013Yale football rivalry|rivalry]]\n| score = 0\u20131\n}}\n}}\n<ref name=SR/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Yale Bulldogs football navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1878 Yale Bulldogs Football Team}}\n[[Category:1878 college football season|Yale]]\n[[Category:Yale Bulldogs football seasons]]\n[[Category:1878 in Connecticut|Yale Football]]\n\n{{collegefootball-1870s-season-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox college sports team season\n| mode = football\n| year = 1878\n| team = Yale Bulldogs\n| image = \n| image_size =  \n| conference = Independent\n| record = 4\u20131\u20131\n| head_coach = None\n| captain = [[Walter Camp]]\n| stadium = [[Hamilton Park (New Haven)|Hamilton Park]]\n \n}}\n{{1878 college football records}}\nThe '''1878 Yale Bulldogs football team''' represented [[Yale University]] in the [[1878 college football season]]. The Bulldogs finished with a 4\u20131\u20131 record. The team recorded five shutouts and outscored its opponents by a combined total of 7 to 1.<ref>{{cite web|title=1878 Yale Bulldogs Schedule and Results|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=SR/College Football|accessdate=February 27, 2017|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/yale/1878-schedule.html}}</ref><ref name=SR>{{cite web|title=2015 Yale Football|url=http://www.yalebulldogs.com/sports/m-footbl/2015-16/files/year_by_year_results_thru_2015.